## Accessibility (WCAG 2.2 Level AA)

All user-facing components MUST meet WCAG 2.2 Level AA. Apply these rules whenever creating or modifying frontend code.

### Semantic HTML & ARIA

- Use semantic elements (`<button>`, `<nav>`, `<main>`, `<table>`) — not styled `<div>` or `<span>`
- Every interactive element must have an accessible name (visible label, `aria-label`, or `aria-labelledby`)
- Icons must have text alternatives (`aria-label` or visually hidden text)
- Tables must have `<th>` headers and descriptive `aria-label`
- Forms must have `<label>` elements associated with inputs via `for`/`id`

### Keyboard Navigation

- All interactive elements must be keyboard focusable
- Logical tab order (follow visual layout)
- No keyboard traps — user can always tab away
- Focus must be visible at all times (`outline` or equivalent indicator)
- Custom components need explicit `tabindex`, `role`, and keyboard event handlers

### Color & Contrast

- **Text**: 4.5:1 minimum contrast ratio (3:1 for large text ≥ 18pt / 14pt bold)
- **UI components**: 3:1 minimum contrast against background
- Color must never be the **sole** method of conveying information (add icons, text, or patterns)

### Forms & Validation

- Every input has a visible `<label>` or `aria-label`
- Required fields indicated programmatically (`aria-required="true"` or `required`)
- Validation errors associated via `aria-describedby`
- Error messages announced to screen readers (via `aria-live` or `role="alert"`)

### Dynamic Content

- Use `aria-live` regions for content that updates without page reload
- Route changes must be announced to screen readers
- Loading states must be communicated (`aria-busy`, loading indicators with text)
- Modals/dialogs must trap focus and return focus on close

### Accessibility Checklist

- [ ] Semantic HTML elements used (not div/span for interactive elements)
- [ ] All interactive elements have accessible names
- [ ] Keyboard navigation works without mouse
- [ ] Focus visible on all focusable elements
- [ ] Color contrast meets minimums (4.5:1 text, 3:1 UI)
- [ ] Form inputs have associated labels
- [ ] Dynamic content uses aria-live regions
- [ ] Modals trap and restore focus

